{"key":"processedPost-13142192","value":{"id":13142192,"first":13140583,"last":13142192,"when":1283528988,"utime":"09/03/10 06:49 PM","cleanedPost":"The shotgun terrarium was designed to be left for several days when necessary.&nbsp; At the time, I was working 12 hour shifts, and often didn't even have time to take care of them after work.&nbsp; You'll be fine in an open room.<br />Now for bad advice above.&nbsp; Don't run a fan in the room.&nbsp; Have a window and/or door partly open, but no fans, which will screw up the natural air currents that the terrarium works on.&nbsp; Don't use an air pump in a shotgun terrarium. Don't use ANYTHING to reduce the area of the terrarium. The CO2 dissipates into the air within the terrarium, so the less air, the higher the concentration of CO2. It's not about air exchanges per hour, it's about maintaining a CO2 level less than 800 ppm.<br />RR"}}